8  Appendix 3 
OUTLINE TERMS OF REFERENCE FOR CONSULTANTS 

A.  Tax Experts (international, 9.8 person-months, four consultants) 

1.  The  main  requirement  for  the  tax  experts  is  strong  tax  accounting  and  statistics 
knowledge. A graduate degree and minimum of 5 years relevant work experience are desirable 
but not mandatory. The experts could be academics, researchers, accountants, statisticians, or 
economists who have worked in the private or public sectors. They must exercise due diligence 
in undertaking processes concerning data compilation and validation. Moreover, they should 
have  good  writing skills. With  input from  the Organisation for  Economic  Co-operation  and 
Development (OECD) and the project team, the experts will 
(i)  compile  and  validate  internationally  comparable  tax  revenue  statistics  using 
OECD methodology; 
(ii)  liaise  with  government  departments,  if  necessary,  to  obtain  government 
accounting data; 
(iii)  analyze the data and draft the report on tax revenue statistics in Asia;1 and 
(iv)  deliver the expected outputs: internationally comparable tax revenue statistics; 
draft, revised, and final reports on tax revenue statistics in Asia. 

B.  Manuscript Editors (international, 1.0 person-month, two consultants) 

2.  The  editors  will  have  experience  editing  Asian  Development  Bank  (ADB)  research 
publications. Under the supervision of the project team leaders, the editors will 
(i)  edit the report on the comparative analysis of tax administration in Asia and the 
Pacific, and the report on tax revenue statistics in Asia: (a) rewrite, reorganize, 
and/or  shorten  the  text  to  improve  its  logical  structure  and  sharpen  the 
arguments;  (b)  simplify  technical  language,  eliminate  jargon,  and  introduce 
definitions so that the chapters can be understood by an educated nonspecialist; 
(c) cut or edit redundant passages and simplify long, complicated sentences; and 
(d) suggest additional materials (e.g., boxes, tables, figures) that would make the 
publication more reader-friendly;  
(ii)  check the manuscript for consistency and accuracy: (a) identify factual errors 
(e.g., by determining whether correct names of institutions and other entities are 
used; checking major statements of fact on leading web sites, where practical); 
and (b) highlight data inconsistencies; 
(iii)  copyedit all parts of the reports in conformity with ADB editorial style and usage; 
(iv)  ensure, to the degree possible, consistency of language style in all parts of the 
publication; 
(v)  edit tables and figures; 
(vi)  ensure that subheads are consistent and logical; 
(vii)  check references to tables, figures, appendixes, bibliographies, and parts of the 
text; 
(viii)  edit notes to make sure the text references are correct; 
(ix)  supervise the encoding of corrections as well as incorporation of tables, charts, 
and boxes; 
(x)  prepare the table of contents, definition of terms, and list of acronyms; and 
(xi)  deliver the expected output: edited manuscript. 


1  All tax experts will be expected to draft sections of the report. One tax expert will be responsible for compiling the 
full report.
